annotation: So the best female player starts off with the most common opening.  We all know about the saying "Best by Test."  But that especially applies to GM's.
And Pavlina responds with the Siclian.  And whereas the King's Pawn Game is most common for most players the Siclian is the most common defense for GM's.
As one would expect.

But this is something that I wouldn't expect.  And in fact I think that it's out of book.  The most common move you'd see is the continuation 2...d6 which is what most of us would have played.  But not this move.

Of course I like this move.  But it's under I guess you can say a faulty technicality.  But it's faulty for me and not anyonelse.  That's because I'd do it to go back to familiar lines like Ruy Lopez since I wouldn't know what to play.  However it's generally not a good idea.  The idea being that ..."when someone plays something that doesn't follow what you know then you must also play something that meets the change in the position".  The question is what move would that be here?
Now this move I understand perfectly well.  In this position Pavlina's goal is to fianchetto her DSB.
Meanwhile Judit decides to castle.  I think that she made the right choice and if I was white and playing the game this is also when I would have castled.
As mentioned earlier black fianchetto's.

I do not know why white played.  Personally I would have continued developing.  One can develop by either advancing the d pawn or bringing the N into play.  I would have played 5.Nc3 in this position.
However black waists no time in continuing to develop.

? But white almost has the same thing in mind.  I understand why JP played this as opposed to d3 as 6.d3 would have blocked her bishop.  However this move is a mistake as it gives away a pawn after a variety of exchanges.  One of the positives that can be taken away however is that white will have compensation later on.

So all is said and done white continues to advance her e pawn.  My guess is that she wants a passed pawn.  The thing is that we're not at the phase yet and that this is not going to become that at all.
In the meantime black takes advantage of her opportunities to continue developing.

The only problem is that white goes on the offense by pinning Pavlina's N.  As a result I would have said that better was 10...Nf6?? except that it could result in the same.  In fact that move would be a serious blunder due to white's e5 pawn.  And 10...Nh6?? is not any better as it would also lose a piece due Judit's DSB.  So was the best move here.

So now black tucks her monarch away.  However the problem is that it allows something that white is about to do.  What is that?  Well it allows JP to win back a pawn because of 11.Qxd4  Having said that castling should have waited for another move this time as best was 10...Bxe5 winning another pawn and putting white further behind.

So black decides to kick her white's Q.  Of course there's more to chess then simply attacking pieces.  So what was the goal?  I believe that it was tempii.  That the idea being was for Pavlina to attack her opponents Q to gain time so that she can then develop.  And black kept in mind that if white were to capture so 12.Bxd8 then black can recapture 12...Nxd4

? However white launches a different attack this time on the K side.  But at the same hitting on black's Q so black must now take action.  The only problem however is that sooner or later it loses a pawn.  That's the only reason as to why this move is a mistake.  And unlike before it's going to be a lot harder to for her to find compensation.  In fact it will be an unusual since white is not going to win back material.

And this is how she does that.  But don't know why.  I guess however black attacks with the idea being tempii because it should force white to retreat her LSB so that black can continue developing.  The only thing is that Judit has one move up her sleeve.

And here it is.  Instead of losing tempo white actually gains time so black did not achieve her goal.  In fact it backfired as 12...Qb6?! actually allowed white to complete development.  The only problem as noted before is that black wins material a free pawn.

!! Yes it's generally very good to do after completing development.  But at first I wasn't sure why white would play this and most certainly wouldn't even give a !.  Reason: with this move black will be able to exchange more material and when you're behind it's generally not a good idea to exchange as it would give you less to defend with.  But that is not the case here.  In fact there's a strategy behind this after that exchange which is what makes this move extraordinarly brilliant deserving a !!  So Pavlina "Better be careful from now on" otherwise white will crush her.

?? Normally a move like this would deserve a !.  But the saying "To take is a mistake" applies here.  Black got overly confident since she was ahead and this was Judit's plan all along.  The idea was to force an exchange and give up a piece.  After which something even bigger is going to happen which is going to seal black's fate.  That's why this move was actually the losing blunder.  Note: What looks good might actually be bad and it's important to be aware of that.
So white's brilliant plan starts with this move.  Therefore as noted Pavlina just walked into a lot of trouble that she won't be able to get out of.

I don't know why black played this.  But this time no matter what she does it does not matter this time.  That's significant you know because everything you and your opponent is essential and therefore should matter as few commentators said in some of my past annotations.  But this is as an exception because no matter what white has an inevitable mating pattern that black cannot get out of.

And after taking the R black resigned.  Unlike the last time resignation is not premature here.  Why?  Well normally you'd think that this is quite bad as that move should win a Q for a R.  But "It's not so easy" as Jack Stockel and Judit Polgar has said.  And there's way to more this then meets the eye.  The reason being is that white now has a mate in two.  17...Kxe8 (forced) 18.Bh6+ Kg8 (forced) Re8#.
An unusual opening leads to approximate opening equality but Black gets an edge in the middlegame when White fails to fix his defects efficiently and wins late as a direct result of early issues.
The Englund Gambit Accepted.  White could have "opted out" with 2.e4 with a counter gambit offer (The Danish/Goring/Scotch Gambit complex).  Interesting also is 2.d5.

Black's options include 2...f6 and 2...d6.  The latter can transpose to a gambit line of Black's in the Philidor.  The Englund Gambit coplex is actually three or four different gambits.  The Soller (2...f6) the Englund (2...Nc6) the Hartlaub (2...d6) and the Blackburne which arises out of the Hartlaub.  I have also experimented with 2...Bc5 then 3...Qe7 and perhaps 4...Nc6 but this is sometimes cumbersome against best play by White and definitely difficult to play under such circumstances.  If white hesitates however...
If White wants to test Black then a different third move is probably needed.  A favorite is 3.Qd5.
Maybe 6.c4 is better?
Wisely unpinning the Queen's Knight immediately before Black can build any significant pressure.

The opening is pretty much over and in taking stock we see Black has a healthy bit of the center and a Queen that might be attacked while White is solid and ready to push e3-e4. If White gets the e4 push in soon the Black Queen may need to take time to move to a safe square.  Dynamic equality?

Initially 10.a3 moves Black's Bishop to a very threatening position.  Which is not particularly strong as White easily parries the mating threat. Most likely the Black Bishop is going to eventually need to re-position so maybe 10.g3 to counter the expected ...Bd6 is convincing? A different plan with Re1 and e4 is in order too.  I suspect 10. a3 is to help implement e3-e4.
Black loses a tempo now but White has weaknesses to attack.  Question is do you think the position at 9....0-0 or 11...Qe6 is easier for White?
An interesting solution!
Maybe 11.g3 (or even 10.g3) was better since White now ends up playing it to stop another mating threat? Seems like it is always easier to see stuff after the fact.
Dreaming of ...Nxg3 sacks....

Apparently White was also dreaming of knight to g3 sacrifices!  White makes certain all I can do is dream about those sacks. I expected 14. Bxe4 however.  White's pawn structure will soon be inferior to Black's. Depending on your viewpoint you might say the same situation existed at move 8.
White wins a pawn...
For a second...
Exchange sacrifice!
Now 18.Qxf5 gxf5 19.Nxd6 cxd6 gives Black a bad pawn structure too.  I do not think it would matter however since the two Rooks will probably be better than the Rook and Bishop in this position.
Stopping the Nf6+ right away.  Maybe the b2 pawn can soon become lunch...
Now 19.Ng5 does not seem convincing to me. The game move seems best for White.
Again trying to keep the Knight off f6.
Obviously I did not do so but at least now the Nf6+ is not as unfavorable for Black.
One exchange sacrifice deserves another!

Dynamic equality again?  Not quite this time.  Black still has the better pawns but a better pawn structure does not confer much as far as winning a game at this point. The weakened pawns do however give Black a target and an ability to formulate clear plans against those targets.  I think I would have traded Queens if I was White.  There would be less in the way of pieces to work against the weaker pawn structure.  The White King and Rook should then be able to hold the draw.
I will argue the earlier Queen (the road not taken) trade would have left an easier to defend pawn structure for White.
The option was 28.Rd1.  Maybe this was better? My hunch is to say affirmative. Hard to say.  For example 28.Rd1 Re8 29.Kf2 b5 still leaves White with some problems to solve.

It was going to be hard to defend the c4 pawn after Black gained control of the e-file.  Obviously contesting that control is important to White's survival.  At this point it is too late and White needs to conjure up a dynamic reply.

Maybe 30.Rd1 was better? White is unable to defend the c2 pawn now. The pawn structure is going from bad to gone.  After 30.Rd1 White could defend c2 although his position would be fast becoming very non-dynamic.  Lacking dynamic counterplay when down material is not a good thing!
The idea is to stop White's only winning chance right away...the supported d5 passer.
White should try to avoid the Rook trade!
Game over.... a passed pawn on both sides means White can not stop Black from advancing to Queendom on at least one side of the board!
Again the defects in my opponent's position allow me to formulate clear and effective plans to further irritate the sore spots.
The loyal Queenside pawns complete their mission by sacrificing for the greater good.
Resigning would be the best move but perhaps a stalemate is possible.... You can not get a draw by giving up!
The stalemate is not likely.

The only constant was White's inferior pawn structure and Black's ability to keep the problem at the forefront.  If White's game is to be improved most likely the first goal would be to avoid the bad structure or at least efficiently correct the issues as soon as possible.
Normal opening
I want to Castle queenside
I don't know what he/she will do with this move
I have castled.
This was his/her first mistake I can take the pawn with the Bishop because the figure is protected by the queen.
I attack the center
Black protect the pawn.
I take it
What will black do with this move?
I take another pawn
I take the Bishop at g7
And Black too
I attack the Bishop
The move was a mistake because I get the Knight with check. Better: Qe5 because the queen is protected by the pawn at f6 and the Queen protect the Knight at h5
All the games start here.
The natural move to complete development and enable castling.
Black wishes to simplify further...
...and I'm amenable.
The skirmish is complete and the position still even.
May as well go through with my plan and castle.
Placing the Knight on the natural square to protect his own K-side.
I centralize *my* Knight.
Black follows suit.
I force him back.
Returning to home base.
Taking the half-open file. If the Exchange Variation is not played on move 7 this is a popular 7th move for White. It is still strong here.

Instead of P-QB4 freeing himself completely Black has to settle for this move that strengthens his Pawn chain. Although with two minor pieces on each side already gone it may be said that Black has already relieved a good deal of the normal cramp in the Orthodox.
With the Rook free I can retire this B without interfering with my other pieces.
Preparing to clear the first rank.
I clear my own connecting my Rooks.
Black likewise connects *his* Rooks. The position is still approximately even.

With this move I begin to prepare a Pawn storm against the White King. I realize this will leave my own King exposed but you can't be a scared chess player. Every attack involves a certain amount of risk.
What had been a slow strategical game [typical of QP openings] ends suddenly...
...on this lightning-bolt!

Hi Everyone!

I have some really mixed emotions here!  On the one hand I am chuffed to gain parity with my on the board nemesis in chief Freddy the Master Mater on the other I somehow feel I could have got even more out of the game if I had had Henry on b1 instead of a1 to allow my knight to interpose a back row check so that my heavies and my g pawn passer could really get to work.  Alas this did not happen and my advantage dissipated and at one time Freddy had a big advantage in the endgame.  Thankfully he slipped up and allowed me back into the game and not only that he found himself playing reluctant host to Glenda and her white steed late on in the game.  Freddy eventually allowed a draw by repetition.  So how did all this come about?  Well read on.......
2. ..... b6!? - Freddy decided to gambit a pawn.  It does open lines for his lsb to bear down on my e4 pawn however so I must watch out here.

4. Bb5+ - although with this check Fou Leblanc has made it very possible for Henry to castle kingside although as far as Freddy is concerned I like to keep him guessing as to where Henry will eventually reside as long as possible.
6. ...... Qxd7 - a plethora of exchanges have cleared the way for Freddy to put his king on the queenside.  I now start to pay attention to developing my queenside.
9. Be3 - it has only taken 3 more moves to almost clear the decks both sides of Henry and it will be four when Glenda moves to d2 on the next turn.
10. ..... d5 - threatening a pawn fork on d4.  In order to avoid this I invite a trade of dsb's.
12. Qxh6 - and Freddy accepts the invitation.  Glenda controls f8 so Freddy goes queenside and I follow suit.
14. f3 - bolstering e4.
15. Ne2 - Freddy exerts a bit of a cramp here and now the Wicked Witch can land on a4.  Yikes!
15. ...... Rhe8 - not yet though!
16..... Nc6 - starting to amass his forces on the queenside.
17. ..... Re5 - now a rook swinger to the queenside.  Ominous.
18. Kb1 - might as well defend a2 and bring the knight across to reinforce it.

20. g3 - I preserve my one pawn advantage by shutting out the wicked witch.  Now I must turn my attention back to the queenside.  I move Henry to a1 where he stays until move 41.  However this move will waste a vital tempo later on which could have made a difference between an Expert Draw and an Expert Victory.  You will see just how!
22. Rf1 - to guard the f pawn.
23. h4 - checks Freddy's kingside pawn roll.
23. .... a4 - now comes one on the queenside!
24. a3 - halts it but for how long?
27. fxg4 - pawn trade.  It looks as though Freddy can play Nxg4 but if he does I will counter with Rxf7+ and my innocuous looking e4 pawn will become a passer.
28. .... Ng4 - a familiar and much dreaded Freddy knight incursion.
29. ...... Ne5 - hmm I was expecting Ne3.

31. Qf2 - I now line up on that f7 pawn and also doubly protect my h4 pawn.  Now over to the Inquest Jury.  Would Kb1 rather than an immediate Rxf7+ on the next turn have made the difference between me being merely jstevens1 or TheBlackQueen?!

34. ..... Qxh4 - after all that plethora of exchanges I have 2 pawns for the exchange.  Unfortunately my passer on g5 is also isolated and it is really weak.  If Henry had been on b1 then Nc1 would allow interposition without loss of the knight to a back row check.  This would allow my rook to join in and defend that weak g pawn and maybe shepherd it to Glendadom.  But Henry is on a1 and not b1 and that is a real headache.  As a result of this over the next fifteen moves or so apart from a few spurts I ended up letting my clock wind down to just over 2 days per move before making a decision.
36. Qe5+ - at least Glenda is aggressively placed but alas she has no support whatsoever at the mo. and Freddy will be able to hide his king - sigh and double sigh!
37. ..... Rc7 - at least Freddy is doing a lot of scratching around at the moment but is he up to something?!
38. Qf6 - Glenda stays in the vicinity of King Freddy watching and waiting.
40. Rc1 - Gameknot analysis cites this as the move that prevents me from becoming TheBlackQueen.  Suddenly from me going from being the equivalent of a pawn up - this advantage turns to Freddy.
41. Kb1 - Finally Henry moves to that b1 square.  Alas it is one move too late to do anything about my poor g5 pawn.
43. Qe8 - so I lose my pawn tears!  However I still plan my counterplay .......

44. Rf8 - for one moment a dark dark shadow looms over King Freddy and he shivers!  Can you the Inquest Jury guess what that shadow represents and what is the move from Glenda that could make King Freddy shiver?
45. Qxf8 - Freddy avoids copping Old Matey by trading rooks.  Now will the Wicked Witch land a check on my back row?

46. Qd5+ - strangely enough he retreats her - he wants to drive Glenda out of his arc.  I keep her there and I submit a draw offer which Freddy declines.  As far as he is concerned it is the 50 move rule for Yours Truly!
48. Qc4 - attacking a4.
49. Qg8 - Glenda does her best to stay in Freddy's camp but boy I think she feels like humming Monsoon's "Ever So Lonely" because she really is a Lone Ranger aaaah!
49. ..... b5 - this now sets the 50 move rule to move 99 provided there are no further pawn moves or captures.  I will then be able to declare the game drawn.
50. Qg2 - Homesick Glenda temporarily returns to her hometown but not for very long.
50. ...... c4 - make that move 100.

52. cxd3 - I must now mark time until Move 102.  However I am slightly happier with my position than I was a few moves back.  For a starters my knight is now a lot more active and it is controlling some vital squares such as c2 and d3.  I suppose that is one advantage of being the exchange down at least a relatively low value piece is defending a pawn to the piece/s that can attack it!
53. Qg6 - Now that she sees that she will have her horse to keep her company she is not quite so averse to the idea of a return trip into Freddy's position.

53. ..... Rh8 - Gameknot Analysis marks this move up as an inaccuracy. Although it does threaten to come down on h1 for a check and the Witch can then check Henry on the a2-g8 diagonal at least the knight can block the check by moving to d5.  However he does not have to do this because King Freddy is about to feel ........
54. Qa6+ - CHEEEECK! ....... the white heat from Glenda!  Freddy however has just one legal move sigh and double sigh and that is to b8.
55. Qb6+ - can the BK run away?  We shall see.

56. ..... Qb7 - Freddy tries to hide his king behind the Witch but Glenda is having none of it.  An observation test for the Inquest Jury here:  If King Freddy plays 56. ..... Kd8?? why is this move a double question mark?
58. Qa6+ - Ah Freddy let's do this dance again!
59. Qe6+ - and again for if he goes back to d7 next turn I am now in a position to declare a ........

60. Qe6+ ...... DRAW!!!  Yup after 60 moves the game is drawn wheew and double wheew.  So much so that after I got the game drawn I googled Youtube and downloaded these tracks to boogie on down in order to release loadsa adrenalin.  http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O972NI6s958 then  http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=otBdxNmEq6k and http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CpP2d5NBoqU.  So after chilling out to those lurvely 80s soul funk grooves I then annotated the game.  There will be more games from me to annotate later on but for now I hope you have all had a good read.  Bye for now - Joanne

My first annotaion of a game.

At this point I'm already trying to calculate what next. My mind is already saying to develop knight's to c3 and b3 as well as Bishops to c4 and e3 but also Rooks on d1 and e1. I also want my queen on f3. My pawn structure should be orientated on attacking the centre achievable by playing f4 h3 and Kb1 to get my King safe.
Black plays the Prins defence perhaps the most solid in this situation.
The classical line.
Najdorf variation : secures b5 from my three minor pieces all poised.
I saw this as the most active continuation.
An important move that although blocks in the c8-bishop contests the centre heavily.
This is to counter Black's two central pawns. My future plans are to pick out pawn targets to castle (most likely queenside) and to play Bc4 h3 and develop my heavy pieces.
A passive yet necessary move.
Browne variation. My pieces are now ready to develop onto stronger squares.

The first move to not be by the book. Computer analysis says this is an innacuray and that Black would have more success with 8...h6 or 8...Qc7. To accord to my plan I am aiming to attack the king or at least limit the movement of Black. However it is also important to note the weakness on b6 and that this is a potential target.
My response is intended to aim at Black's kingside. The h7-pawn is a real weakness.
Strong : Forces my d4-knight to stay in the centre or control it from afar.
I saw this as possibly the best move. Black's c6-knight isn't extremely strong and so I didn't want to swap off mine.
?! In my opinion a dubious move. I can now put a pre-meditated plan into action - To make Black's pieces (namely the Bishops) useless and poorly situated.

You will now notice several positional plusses for me. Firstly Black's c8-bishop has one square to move to. Secondly the f6-bishop is now the only defender to Black king. Furthermore the d6-pawn is now a backwards pawn and liable to attack. Also the d5-square is now weak enough for me to attack the f6-bishop thereby removing the defender. Also a pawn march is now a potential threat. I also have my eyes on 1. h4 Bxh4? 2. Qh3... +/-.
A strong move. My bishop can't move else 13...Nxc2+. Also d5 is now partly covered.
The loss of the bishop isn't costly. I now have central dominance piece placement is better and a potential attack is formulating.
The d6-pawn is now seriously weak.
This has the benefit of limiting the c3-knight's activity but also of providing a square for the c8-bishop not to mention one which can attack the weak e4-pawn.
Qxd6 is now a serious threat. However Be7 leads to a pawn onslaught so maybe a single pawn isn't too important....?
?! Black prefers development over material.

!?  After long thought I believed that this was an answer - an experiment. Yes 16. Kb1!... leads to poor counterplay for Black but this looked interesting and I didn't want to pass up the opportunity. There is no material threat - 16...Bxh4 17. Qh3? Bg5+ and Black is relatively safe. However after I gambit the pawn away I end up with strong pieces and a poorly placed bishop for Black.
As I expected.
If he swaps my rook will lead to a heavy attack.
?!  As I stated earlier the bishop is now poorly placed on h4..... but now for a little longer!
My king is FINALLY secure.
Strong tempo move. The e5-pawn is free but a variation is possible to pick him up again.

?? This move effectively costs the game. Black had two main options. One was the defensive 19... h6 which secured an average endgame albeit a pawn down. However the more aggresive and striking option was 19... Bg3! which would lead to complications for me in the centre and give Black a chance to win his pawn back with 20. Qc5 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Qf4 and strong play from Black would secure a strong endgame.
At this point some form of disaster is inevitable.
Also favoured by the computer.
Black can get some compensation in the form of central pawns for his bishop.
Covers c2 but also attacks the queen.
?? If 23... Qg6 an alternative variation was 24. Rde1 Bf5 25. Nxf5 Qxf5 26. Re5! [ 26...Qxe5 27. Qxh7#] 26...Qg6 27. Rg5!...
1-0 Thankyou to my opponent for this game!
So I got in the habit of playing this ONLY because it was said to be Bobby Fischer's favorite 1st move.
And the Sicilian...
Now there are better moves than what I do as white next. Yeah yeah I know I could move Nc3...
At this point black has what he wants; a superior center with excellent counter-attacking chances. So black ought to just pursue playing that way or so I would think.
Because I don't know all the continuations now as many of you know them I make this quiet move causing black to think as this surely isn't the best white response.
Black makes a decent reply and threatens to crash down in the center. I for one am glad his bishop isn't going down that diagonal. Not yet anyways!

I play c4 indicating that I hope to play in the fashion of the Maroczy bind trying to tie up the center but black is positioned so that this should not occur. I've found that in these kinds of positions black often underestimates the strength of kingside attacks which will be my goal here. This much I do know: black can thwart this in one of two ways; a break involving ...f5 or ...d5. Which will he choose?
He chooses to develop preparing to first castle before committing.
This position is slightly favorable to black but at least white has the initiative for the moment.
Prophylactic move; black will not have time for Ng4; the best thing for black now may be that central push which will immediately cause white problems since ...d5 is very good here.
However black chooses ...d6 when d5 was much better. Still playable along with Rb8 or even Re8 however. But not as strong as ...d5.
I choose the best response; Bg5.
Will he or won't he? Yes he will. Black asks the question. Rb8 was slightly better here however.
Far and away the best move for white now.
Here white chooses Rb8 after moving the white bishop off of the c1-h6 diagonal. ...Bd4 was also playable.
And here I make an inaccuracy. Better was Qc2. This eventually costs me a tempo and could (should?) have cost the game. Perhaps Nc3 was the best move in this position but perhaps not.
What else? ...g5 was a good choice too depending on black's long-term strategies.
Only one move now for white Nc3. All other moves and black will be much better than white. As things are now black is definitely better.

Inexplicably however black now chooses a5 which is not a bad move but where is the fit with the position here? ...g5 or ...Bg4 or even ...Be6 were both good choices. Bd7 is playable but a bit passive. a5 will be useful but... I think it's a bit early here allowing white some time. Which I need. Lucky me...

Other than moving one of the rooks f3 was possible. Fritz considered Na4 too but I did not; it's generally not good to position knights out of the action of course because with careful play an opponent can capitalize on the tempos it would take to bring that knight back into the board. And I did not feel like calculating a zillion or so moves to see if Na4 would be okay or not.

This was one of the crucial positions of the game. As tempting as it might be for some to think taking on c3 would be good for black a closer look reveals it may not be. My opponent saw this but unfortunately did not see the best move here. Ba6 seemed kind of awkward to me and to Fritz. Fritz much preferred Be6 or g5; Qe7 is also playable.

And I made a blunder here but my opponent did not see the combination that would have won him a pawn. Can you spot it? Stop and look for it. Not too hard to spot but this was blitz after all. Anyways Qc2 was the correct move for white. Also playable was Nd1. Rfc1 was one of Fritz's other choices but my desire was to play f4 at some point soon so I did not even look at that. This was also why I missed the possible loss of the pawn. To win a pawn black responds simply 15...Bxc3 Qxc3 Nxe4 Bxe4 Qxh4 Rfe1 (due to the bishop xray) Qxf2 Bxc6 and things are looking difficult for white.
Lucky for me black did not wish to part with his bishop pair and did not even consider looking further. Nxe4 was also possible.
So I choose the best response here and the opportunity for black to win a pawn evaporates.
All of this positioning to fight over d5 causes black to lose what could have been had. White's move now is rather obvious and I waste no time in moving my knight. Other moves are not nearly as good.
Provided I make no more blunders I finally have a small advantage now.
F4 was better. I played a bit too cautiously here.
With the knight gone now I move f4 effectively wasting another tempo. But the pressure on my king is more palatable with that knight gone so... bleh. At least I'm trying to make my plan work.
Better was ...exf4 after which black is better. But with this move white has an opportunity to have a lasting advantage. I take it...

Possibly the wrong rook to move by black in this position. The last few moves were all good moves as we maneuver. I can force the black queen to move but eschew that for the moment; I am going to obfuscate. That is I will create a plan on the queenside that black will counter then pursue my real plan on the kingside and hope black cannot react quickly enough. Yeah that's right. I thought this stuff up all right but I could not see far enough ahead in the time I had to think to know if things would work out or not. As it turns out it does but not by much.
...d5 or ...a4 were good choices. This choice I'm not so sure about.
b4 was also good here but this is the best continuation at this point.
White maintains a good space advantage at this point.

And now it is my turn to miss a combination beginning with exd5! after that we could have ...c5 Qe3 Qc7 Bf2 Rd6 b5 Nb4 and black is really cramped or perhaps ...cxd5 c5 and black will lose a piece. Other continuations all seem even better for white! But instead of any of that we get...

c5. Way to go idiot me. ;) White is still standing very well now but I'm really wanting to assault the king and black is threatening to bust open the middle. Not much I can do about it now after my last move.
Fortunately black chooses a response that gives me the smallest chance of keeping the middle from opening up.
And black responds of course correctly... well according to Fritz. But I think taking here would have been better opening up the middle; black needs counterplay...
So no taking here either.

Any of the queen moves are rather similar. I choose this move to stop the pawns from advancing while I reposition for my kingside push cleverly disguised (if I must say so myself lol) as defending the queenside.
And has black stymied the queenside? Sure looks like it. Undeterred I continue...
The first real indication that I might have something else planned besides the queenside. However my opponent doesn't realize the significance of the bishop move. Yet.
And here I am about to show my real intentions. I had to think and realized that I would not easily get to the kingside if I allowed c3 to become occupied so had to make this ungainly rook move...
Better for black was doubling his rooks up on the a file.

Now after this move black became suspicious realizing that my moves were really doing nothing over on the queenside. What was I really up to? It's easy to spot so he tries to prevent it although Qf8 was a much better way to try...
This I could not stand for!
So... rather obvious now...
I figured I had time to give my King an out.

Qf8 was much better than this blunder. Black has sealed off his queen from pressuring the queenside and failed to protect the h6 pawn thinking instead to rid himself of the white bishop but doing so is much much too slow for this position.

So slow in fact that I decide to hide my king altogether before proceeding. In actuality I'm just lucky he did not move Qf8 here. How can my opponent fail to see the imminent danger in retrospect is hard to understand.
The ill-fated black defense.
Bxh6! How many times must we see a sacrifice on the h pawn to know how bad things can get over there?
There are many defensive tries here all resulting in 'ruinous' loss of material. This one is the worst choice alas. Mate will be forced soon now there is not much for black to do.
Alas 45...Nc3 was black's last try to defend with a plus 7.5 score for white. Mate in four two ways to get there. I choose the easiest.
And now I carelessly move. Qxg6+ followed by Qg8# was correct.

THIS time I gave thought to the mate; ...Ke8 Qh8+ and with the knight coming to f6 it's all over. Black resigned here. So some simple misdirection all along planning to sacrifice on h6 if I could. I had a lot of help of course by my opponent in this blitz game. Unless I'm mistaken most proper Sicilian black moves try to get white castled on the queenside since black hopes to attack down that side. With my King untroubled over on the kingside black's remaining pieces are very much unprepared to help defend his own king directly or indirectly.

The only way I could create counterplay.

But I got lucky. Black played an inaccurate move. Much better was pawn takes pawn black having tactics if I took on Rc5 i.e. 53. Rxc5 Rb3+ 54. Rc3 RxR winning the bishop. If Black would have taken the pawn I would not take it back immediately.

Now the game is simplified which is to my taste. I have threats to promote a pawn on both sides of the board. Theoretically it is either win or a draw for me at this point so I got my confidence back.

Without playing ...Nf6 first this allows me to play the Maroczy Bind.  Once quite the feared weapon from White indeed at one point it was  considered a positional blunder from Black to allow it! However since then  play has been found for Black and in 1995 John Nunn and Joe Gallager write  "Although the Maroczy Bind is slightly passive for Black players such as  Larsen Petursson and Velimirovic have shown that by patiently waiting for a  lapse of concentration from White this line can offer winning chances for  Black. The theoretical opinion is that White should maintain a slight  advantage but no one should believe that this is a line in which White  cannot lose." and in the 15th MCO Nick de Firmian says that "With 5.c4  White...leads to a quiter positional type of game yet Black will get  strangled if he/she cannot find active play".
A move that I  have not seen before it seems to only help White develop but I am concious  of the ability for the Queen to quickly reach the Kingside and for the pin to  leave e4 undefended.

After this move I felt that I must win the  game this early sortie from Black's Queen now cannot be condonded. I sat at  the board and convinced myself that I should win after two seeming  tempo-losing moves from Black. When Rossolimo originally started playing 3.Bb5 he wanted to castle as early as move four and then go on the attack.

So what do we learn here: in the opening make more development moves rather than just pushing pawns. Tempo is not a term we higher rated players throw around. We must move 1 or 2 pawns develop all minor pieces (Bishops and Knights) off of the back rank and castle the king to safety. Of course we must parry any threats along the way put forth by our opponent. The pawns should either occupy the central squares or allow for the development of our minor pieces to influence it (as when we fianchetto a bishop for example to g2 g7 or b2 b7). I do commend stealth-invader for putting forth a valiant effort and some of his moves do indicate he is capable of being a great player.

On tour in 1964 I experimented with 5 N-B5. If then 5... Q-B2 6 B-Q3 BxB 7 NxB P-K3 White has more space and the Knight discourages ...P-QB4 or ...P-K4.
More usual is the immediate... N-Q2 to prevent N-K5.
White can try to exploit Black's move order by 8 N-K5 but 8... B-R2 9 B-QB4 P-K3 10 Q-K2 N-Q4! (followed by ...N-Q2) equalizes.
10... Q-B2 11 P-B4 N/1-Q2 12 B-B3 P-QR4! equalizes.
12... B-Q3! 13 B-K4 B-B5! simplifies.
Now Black can no longer force the exchange of Bishops.
The start of a faulty concept. 13.. B-Q3 14 N-K4 B-B5 ch 15 K-N1 N-K4! 16 NxN BxN equalizes.
He still has time to back out with 14... Q-B2.
Now there is no turning back.
A clear refutation. The Queen's retreat is cut off and the weakness on Black's KB2 etched sharply.
What else?

Though the Caro-Kann and I had somewhat of a falling out a little way ago because I kept getting in traps and tactics from white I began to believe in its power again after I won a wonderful game against a street chess hustler in Kiev.
I was playing Nd7 here before which is favored by Karpov one of my heroes. But I don't think it was really to my taste and I finally switched to the main line.

All moves have been standard until this move. This is a lesser-known continuation but I thought it gave black more counterplay than usual. The black queen eyes the e4 and b2 pawns while allowing queenside castling and the eventual joining of rooks. More common is Ngf6 or e6.
An interesting progression: though white is a bit open on the queenside he still castles there. This shows that White is ready for a fight.

Though I usually prefer bishops over knights in most positions I thought that giving my opponent a worse pawn structure was a good idea. In retrospect though I think this capture was not so beneficial as it opens up the f-file so white can attack my king more readily. To avoid the fork on c5 better was probably Bf4+.
Making a double attack on the h5 and a2 pawns though after a supposed Nxh5 black can easily counter with Bc3. A better move was probably castling or Rc8/Rd8.
Now it becomes clear that taking the knight before on g3 was not a smart choice. The f-file is successfully being used by white and his plan is quite clear.
I eliminate the knight so his attacking material and power lessens.
Now that I gained a tempo I start progressing with my own attack on the queenside.
White chooses to attack now in the center since my knight controls the f7 square easily.
At this point or somewhere around this point I offered a draw believing that both of us had no chances to move forward with any advantage. Obviously my opponent refused the draw offer.
Exchanging queens would definitely be in his favor so I come back to keep my drawing chances alive. White has an imposing position though it is unclear as to what he is supposed to do.
I think this may have been a fault of white. This allows my queen more freedom after the exchange that follows.

White wants to hunt the b6 pawn but actually this move is a serious miscalculation. Black gains winning chances with this move as white gives away the g5 square which my queen can occupy with great effect. If white took with the pawn instead black would gain the pawn eventually by the king maneuvering to f7-e6 after a pawn advances.
I think White did not see this continuation and counted on an exchange on d6 or my defense of the b6 pawn.
White cannot defend the g4 pawn and taking the b6 pawn leads to capturing on e6 with check and ensuing tactics or taking on g4 with an attack on the rook.

I enjoy paralyzing moves like these. White has no good continuations - there is tactics that can happen with Qb6+ and Rd2 if the rook moves away - if Qb2 then checkmate on b6 with the queen - if black exchanges rooks I get a dangerous passed pawn.

(!)  I saw that white could get some counterplay with Qa8 then Qe4+ with me pushing g6 eventually and getting in trouble with a possible perpetual on f6-d8. With this move I secure my passed pawn's future while cutting out white's counterplay. 

Though my opponent had some right to refuse my draw offer as he had some chances still in retrospect he should have been more wary my possible counterplay. 

My play was inaccurate at some points and led to my opponent gaining tempo and the momentum. Though at the right time near the end I played fairly on point and didn't give my opponent rest until I had a large advantage. It shows that even though a game seems drawn or even worse for oneself it can turn out to be the opposite with special attention to accuracy.

This quick game was an unexpected win against a player ranked 300+ points above me. I often play a defensive game against players ranked much higher than me but this time I went on the offense.
Usually I do a Ruy-Lopez opening but this time I tried a variation of it.
Move pawn up to free up the dark square bishop so it can pin the knight on the f6 square.
Move bishop to safety and where it can pin the f7 pawn.
Pinned the black knight hoping to go after it with my knight on c3 and then disrupt the black king's castle.
I could respond to the h6 pawn move by either pulling the bishop back to h4 or by exchanging the bishop for a knight. I go for the exchange.
By interposing the knight between the black queen and bishop the only piece protecting that bishop is the pawn in front of the king. This works towards my tactic of disrupting the kingside pawns.
Now black has two unprotected pawns near his king and the third pawn is pinned by the bishop.
Move knight up to where it can threaten the unprotected h6 pawn.

Move queen into the arena. At this point I don't think black can save the h6 pawn. Moving the king to h7 is suicide. Moving the knight to f4 threatens the white queen for just one half move and the game ends shortly after that. So black's best move is to take the knight.
And the pawn takes the bishop and threatens the knight.

The white queen could either stay put and protect the f5 pawn from the knight or it can clear up the area around the black king by taking the h6 pawn. It is better to take the h6 pawn because even if black takes the unprotected f5 pawn the queen might get the knight as a prize in return.
Black takes the pawn as expected ...
And the queen moves to threaten both king and unprotected knight. The queen is safe from the f7 pawn because it is pinned by the b3 bishop. If black moves the king white gets the knight as a prize.
Only safe move for black.
Get rook ready to move to the h column.

This move protects both the f7 pawn and allows the black queen to move to the kingside quickly. Black could have blocked the white bishop with the d-pawn followed by another pawn to c6 one move later to support the d-pawn. That would relieve the pressure on the f7 pawn and allow it to take the queen on g6. If black moved the d pawn this move instead I would have moved my queen to h6.

But the rook can move to the h column quickly anyway. (I should have moved the rook to e4 instead where it can then move to h4 without being threatened by the black queen.) Black resigned at this point.
